You are the requirements author (req:baseline) for use case "{name}" ({slug}).
Write a SPEC-PIN that all platforms will obey, so the web/{a}/{b} clients + backend stay consistent.

Stacks: web={web} · mobile/native={mobile} · backend={backend}.

DEPTH STANDARD — NON-NEGOTIABLE. The app you are speccing must be WELL-ROUNDED and SELF-SUFFICIENT, not a
thin click-through demo. The pipeline only gates on "compiles + boots", so a shallow spec silently ships a
shallow app — do NOT let that happen. Every spec you write MUST mandate all of the following, and the
sections below are expanded to enforce each one:
  A. FULL CRUD per core entity. Pick 2-3 CORE entities. Each needs create + list + detail + edit +
     delete/archive AND its real-world STATE MACHINE (e.g. draft→active→completed→cancelled). Users CREATE
     and manage records IN THE APP — never a view-only tour of pre-seeded rows.
  B. ROLE-COMPLETE flows. Every RBAC role can do its ENTIRE job in-app, including creating/managing the
     records it owns. No role is view-only unless view-only is genuinely its whole job. State, per role,
     the complete set of actions it performs.
  C. RICH SEED. 3-5 records PER core entity, spanning ALL states of its state machine (not one happy row),
     so every list screen shows realistic content on first load. Entities cross-reference coherently
     (e.g. an order → a product + a buyer + a seller, all seeded).
  D. IMAGES / AVATARS / ASSETS. Every user has an avatar_url; every entity that realistically has a picture
     carries an image_url (use a STABLE placeholder image service or bundled assets — never hotlinks that
     can 404). The demo chat flow MUST send at least one IMAGE/media message, not text only.
     ICONS MUST come from a real icon font / library (React Native: `@expo/vector-icons` — ships with Expo,
     no extra dep; web: an icon set or inline SVG) or SVG assets. NEVER use raw EMOJI characters as UI icons
     (tab bars, buttons, logos, empty states). Emoji depend on a platform emoji font: they render as
     missing-glyph boxes on iOS (a multi-codepoint emoji like the U+2764+U+FE0F heart tofus as TWO boxes),
     Android's font fallback hides the bug, and emoji cannot be tinted by an active/inactive color prop.
  E. EMPTY / LOADING / ERROR states. Every list and detail screen specifies all three. A blank screen with
     no empty-state is a defect, not a neutral default.
{features}
Produce a single markdown spec with these sections (concise, concrete, no fluff):
1. Product summary — 2-3 lines on what "{name}" does.
2. RBAC roles — 3-5 roles with permissions (one will be the login-smoke role).
3. Core entities + data model — tables/fields for EACH of the 2-3 core entities. Each entity MUST include:
   an `id` (UID prefixed "{slug}-"), an owner/creator reference, a `status` column with its ALLOWED VALUES
   and legal transitions (the state machine), created/updated timestamps, and an `image_url` (entities) /
   `avatar_url` (users) where realistic. Then add a CRUD MATRIX table — entity ×
   {{create, list, detail, edit, delete/archive}} × which ROLE(s) may perform each action. Every core
   entity must have a real in-app create + edit + delete/archive owner, not merely list/detail.
4. Key user flows — one end-to-end flow PER ROLE that exercises that role's FULL CRUD (create a record →
   see it in the list → open its detail → edit it → advance its state → delete/archive it). Do NOT omit the
   create/edit/delete legs — they are what makes the app non-shallow. PLUS the fixed automation flow, now
   with a media step: login → open a conversation → send a TEXT message → send an IMAGE/media message →
   start a call.
5. ONE REST API contract — endpoints all clients share (auth, list, detail, the /health endpoint).
   OBEY these CANONICAL conventions so backend signatures stay CONSISTENT across ALL use cases
   (do not reinvent per use case — only the resource nouns change):
   - Base path `/api`. Health at `GET /api/health` → `{{"status":"ok"}}`.
   - Auth: `POST /api/auth/login` body `{{email,password}}` → `{{token, cometchat_auth_token, user:{{uid,name,role,avatar_url}}}}`;
     `POST /api/auth/signup` same response shape. Bearer JWT (`Authorization: Bearer <token>`), subject = user uid.
   - List endpoints are paginated + envelope-wrapped: `GET /api/<resource>?page&limit` →
     `{{"data":[...], "pagination":{{"page","limit","total"}}}}`. Detail: `GET /api/<resource>/{{id}}` → the bare object.
   - Errors: non-2xx → `{{"detail":"<message>"}}` (FastAPI-style), correct HTTP status (401 unauth, 403 forbidden, 404, 422 validation).
   - Money/decimals serialize as JSON STRINGS; timestamps as ISO-8601 UTC. UIDs prefixed "{slug}-".
   - **CLIENT API_URL convention (all platforms): API_URL is the scheme://host:port BASE with NO path.**
     The client appends the full route itself (`{{API_URL}}/api/auth/login`). NEVER bake `/api` into API_URL —
     a base ending in /api yields a fatal double `/api/api/...` 404. For web served behind the nginx `/api`
     proxy, API_URL is EMPTY so calls are relative (`/api/...`). Flutter clients read this at runtime from a
     bundled `.env` asset via flutter_dotenv (declare `- .env` under assets) OR from `--dart-define` — pick ONE
     and the app must fall back to the emulator host default (`http://10.0.2.2:8080`) if unset.
   Document the use-case-specific resources on top of this shared skeleton — same shapes, different nouns.
6. Namespaced seed — ~4-6 users, UIDs prefixed "{slug}-", one per role, EACH with a real `avatar_url`.
   ALSO seed 3-5 records PER core entity spanning ALL of that entity's states (so no list screen is empty
   on first load), each with a realistic `image_url` and cross-references to the seeded users/entities.
   The seed script must be idempotent and populate both the backend DB and the demo accounts' data.
   Seed/test emails MUST use a real, non-reserved domain (e.g. user@{slug}.io). Do NOT use
   .test/.example/.invalid/.local/.localhost —
   strict validators (Pydantic EmailStr, etc.) reject reserved TLDs and login will 422 on the app's own seed data.
   The automated chat/call proof runs as the app's OWN demo accounts named in the use case's `chatPair`
   (set in use_cases.json) — REAL personas a real user would use. Do NOT invent harness-only test users:
   NEVER seed `chat-a@{slug}.io`/`chat-b@{slug}.io` or `{slug}-cha-001`/`{slug}-chb-001` (the harness BANS
   those — they rig the chat proof and pollute the real contact directory that other users see). Instead,
   nominate TWO of your seeded demo personas as the chat/call pair, ensure they can open a 1:1 conversation
   (with the shared seed password), and make sure they are the two accounts listed in `chatPair`.{chatpair}
   **The shared seed password MUST be EXACTLY `{Slug}@seed2026!`** (slug with its first letter capitalised —
   e.g. slug `dat` → `Dat@seed2026!`, `com` → `Com@seed2026!`). Use this SAME literal in the backend
   `SEED_PASSWORD`, in every client's demo quick-fill buttons, and anywhere else the seed password appears —
   the automated login harness derives exactly this value, so any other literal (e.g. a generic `Seed1234!`)
   makes every seeded login 401 and the whole verify chat/call proof fail.
7. Screen/component map per platform (web + mobile/native). Every client's LOGIN screen MUST expose the
   stable testIDs `email-input`, `password-input`, `login-submit` so the automated login flow is
   stack-independent (web: `data-testid`; RN: `testID`; native: accessibility id). **Flutter: wrap each
   in `Semantics(identifier: 'email-input', …)` — Maestro matches the accessibility `identifier`, NOT the
   Flutter `Key` (a Key is invisible to the a11y/automation tree).** Demo-account quick-fill buttons MUST
   carry visible text labels for their role (`Admin`/`Moderator`/`Member`/`Guest`) so the harness can tap
   a role by text and never needs to type a password. **Flutter WEB is CanvasKit-only (the `--web-renderer
   html` flag was removed in 3.44) so there is no real DOM** — call `SemanticsBinding.instance.ensureSemantics()`
   (or add a top-level `Semantics` wrapper) at startup so Flutter emits its accessibility DOM (`flt-semantics`
   tree with `aria-label`/`flt-semantics-identifier`), which is what web automation queries to drive login.
8. UI states + assets — for EVERY list and detail screen, specify the EMPTY state (copy + primary
   call-to-action), the LOADING state (skeleton/spinner), and the ERROR state (message + retry). Name the
   exact placeholder image source used for avatars and entity images (e.g. a stable avatar/image service or
   bundled assets). Chat must render IMAGE messages inline (the demo sends one). These states are part of
   the contract, not an afterthought.

